{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":14614,"record_hash":"sha256:e78c78e99b3da28f9ee20f812e9930412b705d6018878f4260ede427dd9d458f","timestamp":"2026-05-09T17:59:07.774Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 10c7e0\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1197\nOutput:\n# Future Use Cases\n\nThis document records the product direction the first agentlog POC should point\ntoward. These use cases are not implemented by the POC, but they shape the data\nmodel.\n\n## 1. Session Handoff\n\nA developer starts an agent session on one machine and wants to continue it on\nanother machine, possibly with another agent.\n\nExamples:\n\n- Claude Code starts the planning locally, then OpenClaw continues on a remote\n  machine where the repository is already available.\n- OpenClaw starts work on a remote machine, then the user continues locally so\n  they can run a desktop app or device-specific tests.\n\nFor this to work later, GitButler needs to capture enough session context into\nGitMeta, move that metadata through Git transport, and expose it on the other\nside in a form that another agent can use. The POC does not serialize, push,\nfetch, or resume a session, but its project-scoped session records should be\ndurable enough to make that possible.\n\nExpected access pattern:\n\n1. fetch or otherwise exchange GitMeta data for the repository\n2. read `gitbutler:agent-sessions` from the `project` target\n3. choose a session, either by recency, user selection, or a future explicit\n   relationship\n4. read `gitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:transcript`\n5. reconstruct useful context from `content_text`, `event_category`,\n   `tool_name`, and redacted `source_record`\n\nThat means the transcript list must be readable without knowing the original\nmachine's file paths, cwd, branch state, or raw provider session id.\n\n## 2. Sharing Session Details\n\nA developer uses an agent to produce a change and opens a pull request. Reviewers\nshould eventually be able to open a GitButler web view showing what happened in\nthe agent session:\n\n- user prompts\n- assistant responses\n- tool calls\n- planning depth\n- discussed edge cases\n- follow-up questions\n\nThis helps reviewers understand whether the generated work was carefully guided\no\n[TRUNCATED]\n## Many-to-Many Relationships\n\nSessions and code review objects are not one-to-one.\n\nOne branch or pull request may involve multiple sessions:\n\n```text\nPR A\n  -> session 1\n  -> session 2\n```\n\nOne session may also contribute to multiple branches or pull requests, especially\nin GitButler where a worktree can contain several active branches and a user may\ncommit different hunks to different destinations:\n\n```text\nsession 1\n  -> feature branch\n  -> bugfix branch\n```\n\nThe durable object should therefore be the project-scoped GitButler agent\nsession. Branches, commits, changes, and pull requests should later reference\nsession keys rather than own the transcript data directly.\n\nThis is especially important for GitButler because a single worktree may contain\nmultiple active branches at once. An agent can produce edits that the user later\nsplits across several branches, so the capture layer should not guess ownership\nfrom the current branch.\n\nFuture relationship keys can look like this:\n\n```text\n<branch/change/commit target>\n  gitbutler:agent-sessions = set<session-key>\n```\n\nThat shape supports:\n\n- sessions that exist before code is written\n- one session associated with many branch or review objects\n- many sessions associated with one branch or review object\n- branch or commit associations being added after capture\n\n## POC Direction\n\nThe first POC should:\n\n- write redacted, shareable-ready `gitbutler:*` keys\n- keep session data on the `project` target by default\n- use a durable session key independent of branches and commits\n- keep source metadata separate from per-record transcript envelopes\n- keep enough normalized fields to support timeline browsing without reparsing\n  every provider-specific record\n- avoid storing local paths, cwd values, branches, or raw provider session\n  ids\n- avoid serialization, push, fetch, sync, branch inference, and PR association\n\nThe POC should not try to solve session merging. A future UX can decide whether\nmultiple provider sessions should be joined into one GitButler-level session.\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-09T17:59:07.774Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}